Chat Interaction Handling Process – WSP Global IT Service Desk

I.  Objective
      To setup a standard process for handling chat contact from WSP Global employees.

II.  Scopes and Limitations:
     a.    Service Desk L1 analysts will be on “Chat On-Ready” status on Genesys to receive chat interactions.
     b.    L1 agents will use the standard Chat Flow for WSP Service Desk.
     c.    L1 will use the standard templates for the chat interaction.
     d.    L1 will have one call back attempt to the business partner when a chat interaction gets disconnected, after the business partner was correctly identified (i.e. only one search result for the name that appeared on the chat session).
     e.    L1 will leave a voicemail message (when VM is available) and send an email to the business partner, after an unsuccessful call back attempt.
     f.     If the business partner is not identified properly (i.e. multiple name results and no way to identify the user) on the disconnected chat, a callback attempt is not needed, and the ticket will be logged under “Default Client Contact”.
     g.    L1 will tag both the “ghost chat” and the disconnected chat (when the user was identified but troubleshooting has not started) as “Dropped Call” on the “Service Desk” Primary Category and set the ticket to “Resolved” state, using “Closed – No Response” as the Closure Reason.
     h.    L1 will follow the 3-strike rule for disconnected chat interactions (when troubleshooting has already started).
     i.     Service Desk analysts will always ask for permission before using remote connection to the end business partner’s computer, when troubleshooting during chat interaction.

III.  Standard templates for Chat Interaction:

Template for initial chat reply:

Thank you for contacting the Global IT Service Desk.
My name is [insert name here]. How may I help you today?




Chat template for verifying call back number, issue and asking for existing ticket:

Thank you, [insert first name of business partner]. Can I have your phone number?

Is this the number I can call you back on, in case this chat gets disconnected?

I understand you need help with . Do you have an existing ticket for this? May I have it?

If yes:
I see. Thank you. Let me pull up that ticket number for you.

If no:
I see. Let me help you with that.




Template for follow-up chat if there is no reply after after 1 minute:

Thank you for contacting the Global IT Service Desk.
Are you still there [insert business partner’s first name here]? How may I help you today?

NOTE: Send same chat after another minute if still no reply.




Template for disconnecting chat if there is no reply after after 2 minutes of no response WITHOUT T/S:

Hello [insert business partner’s first name here]. We have not received any response from you and we regret to inform you that we will now disconnect this chat session.

Thank you for contacting the Global IT Service Desk. Have a Good day!




Template for disconnecting chat if there is no reply after after 2 minutes of no response DURING T/S:
(Create a ticket and set it to resolved status – no response from user)

Hello [insert business partner’s first name here]. We have not received any response from you and we regret to inform you that we will now disconnect this chat session.

Thank you for contacting the Global IT Service Desk. Please take note of Incident Ticket [insert ticket# here] for your reference. Have a Good day!




Sample Probing questions for T/S (consult KB/SOP guides for additional information required):

•    When did the issue start? Has it happened before this instance?
•    Is there an error message? Were you able to get a screenshot?
•    Which application are you using and what were you trying to do when the issue started?
•    Did you try any troubleshooting step on your own?
•    Are you in the office or are you working remotely?
•    Have you tried the following steps? (provide steps from applicable KB)




Chat template for redirecting business partner to Service Request or Regional Online form:

For your concern with [insert request here], please fill out the Service Request Form / Regional Online form, by clicking on the link below.

Provide link to the Service Request or Region-specific form.




Chat template to verify resolution:

Has your concern been resolved?

If Yes:
Great! Would you like to take note of the steps that we have done to resolve it, or what you can try to prevent it from happening again? (If business partner says yes, advise KB article or offer to send the steps via email).

If No:
We are sorry that the issue has not been resolved. For further assistance, we will send the ticket to the [insert Support Group], and expect a follow-up contact within 24 hours.

NOTE: Please do not provide the exact escalation group name in ServiceNow




Chat template for offering further assistance:

Is there anything else that I can assist you with today?

If No:
Thank you for calling the Global IT Service Desk. Please take note of your Incident Ticket number [insert ticket# here], for your reference. An automated email notification from ServiceNow will also be sent to your email address. Have a good day!

If Yes
I see. Let me open another Incident Ticket for you regarding your concern with [insert new issue here].

NOTE: Proceed to address the next issue.




Email Interaction Handling Process – WSP Global IT Service Desk

I.  Objective
      To setup a standard process for handling email communication with WSP Global employees.

II.  Scopes and Limitations:
     a.    Service Desk L1 analysts will receive email interaction from business partner via Genesys.
     b.    L1 will utilize Genesys to communicate with business partners, only for email interactions that came through Genesys.
     c.    Response time to all email interactions is within 30 minutes.
     d.    L1 will log the contents of the email on the affected business partner’s name on ServiceNow.
     e.    L1 will log the initial email from the user on the “Description” field of the Incident Ticket, and the subject/main concern on the “Short Description” field.
     f.     L1 will use the standard templates for the initial email reply, depending on what the initial email is about.
     g.    L1 will log the email reply made to the user on the “Work Notes” field on the Incident Ticket.
     h.    L1 will make a call back on email issues that require troubleshooting over the phone or remote session.
     i.     L1 will leave a voicemail message (when VM is available) and send an email to the end business partner, after an unsuccessful call back attempt.
     j.     L1 will use the standard email templates applicable to the ticket/issue.
     k.    L1 will follow the 3-strike rule for all active email tickets when there is no further interaction from business partner.

III.  Email Communication SOP:
     a.    Use the business partner’s first name on the salutation, in proper capitalization.
     b.    Follow the appropriate template, and standard font size and color.
     c.    Avoid copying the whole email thread on the “Work Notes” field, for more efficient reviewing and tracking. Only the most recent reply/email sent to the business partner should be logged on the corresponding “Work note”.
     d.    Always use the following format on the subject field when a ticket number is available:

Subject: complete incident ticket#: short description of the issue on the ticket

IV. Standard templates for Email Interaction:

Template for initial email reply that requires additional information:

Hi [name of business partner]


Good day!

Thank you for contacting the Global IT Service Desk.

We have created Incident Ticket number [insert ticket# here], for the concern about [insert issue here]. Can you please provide us more information by answering the questions below?

[list probing questions related to issue.]

For immediate assistance over the phone, please give us a call at [insert Regional SD phone# here], and quote your ticket number [insert ticket#].


[name of SD analyst]

Incident Ticket Follow-up Process – WSP Global IT Service Desk

I.  Objective:
      To setup a standard ticket follow-up process for all WSP Service Desk analysts.

II.  SOP’s:
     •    SD will use the “Customer Visible” Notes field on the Incident Ticket” for sending emails to follow-up non-Email tickets.
     •    When the business partner replies to the follow-up email and it goes through the Genesys queue, then the succeeding outbound emails can be sent from Genesys by utilizing the “reply” option.

A.  Disconnected call/chat:
     a.    Go on “follow-up” status and inform the Queue Manager right away that there was a disconnected call/chat.
     b.    Call the business partner back to continue the assistance and document next steps on the "work notes" on the ServiceNow ticket.
     c.    If the business partner is not identified properly (i.e. multiple name results and no other way to identify the user) on the disconnected call/chat, a callback attempt is not needed, and the ticket will be logged under “Default Client Contact”.
     d.    If unable to reach business partner, leave a voicemail (if VM is available), AND send an email using the template for disconnected call/chat.
     e.    Incident Tickets logged for disconnected call/chat session where troubleshooting has not started will be tagged as “Resolved” with Closure Reason as “Closed – No Response”.
     f.     Voice Mail Template:


"Hello [name of BP]. This is [name of SD tech] from the Global IT Service Desk. We regret that the call/chat got disconnected. For further assistance, please call us back at [insert regional phone # here]. Thank you and have a good day".





     g.     Template for disconnected call/chat where troubleshooting has not started:
(i.e. the business partner has provided his information and main concern but no T/S has been done yet):

Hi [name of business partner]


Good day!

We regret that the call/chat got disconnected. We would like to continue assisting you, but was not able to reach your phone number [insert dialed phone #’s].

For further assistance, please give us a call at [insert Regional SD phone# here], and we are happy to assist you.


[name of SD analyst]
Global IT Service Desk
Servicedesk@help.wsp.com




     h.      Template for disconnected call/chat, in the middle of T/S:
(i.e. if the call got disconnected while troubleshooting with business partner, or was connected to the pc remotely):

Hi [name of business partner]


Good day!

We regret that the call/chat got disconnected. We would like to continue assisting you, but was not able to reach your phone number [insert dialed phone #’s].

[insert additional instructions to users, if applicable]

For further assistance over the phone, please give us a call at [insert Regional SD phone# here], and quote your Incident ticket number [insert ticket#].


[name of SD analyst]
Global IT Service Desk
Servicedesk@help.wsp.com




B.  Unable to reach business partner after callback request to continue T/S:
     a.    If a business partner requests a callback to continue T/S, verify available callback time and alternate phone number.
     b.    If the requested callback time is within the L1’s shift, the L1 should own the appointment.
     c.    If the L1 is engaged in another call/chat at the time of the appointment, the L1 will inform the Queue Manager.
     d.    If the requested callback time is not within the L1’s shift, the L1 should inform the business partner that another L1 will callback.
     e.    The ticket should be endorsed via internal email to the supervisor-on-duty, so that it can be endorsed to an available L1.
     f.     If unable to reach the business partner at the appointed callback time, leave a voicemail (if VM is available).
     g.    Send the business partner an email, using the template for failed callback for T/S.
     h.    VM Template for Unsuccessful callback to continue T/S:


"Hello [name of BP]. This is [name of SD tech] from the Global IT Service Desk. We would like to continue assisting you on [ticket#] about [main issue]. Please reply to the email we will send you shortly. Thank you and have a good day".





     i.    Template for unsuccessful callback to continue T/S:

Hi [name of business partner],


Good day!

We were not able to reach your phone number [insert dialed phone #’s], on the agreed callback time, to continue the troubleshooting for your [insert concern here].

[insert additional T/S or information for the user, if applicable]

For further assistance, please give us a call at [insert Regional SD phone# here] and quote your Incident ticket number [insert ticket#].


[name of SD analyst]
Global IT Service Desk
Servicedesk@help.wsp.com

     a.    If the business partner sends an email or opens a self-service ticket to report an incident, we need to call back for T/S (if enough information is provided on the email/self-service ticket).
     b.    Email interactions will come to the queue on Genesys, while Self-service Tickets will be assigned by the queue manager of the shift.
     c.    If unable to reach business partner, leave a voicemail (if VM is available):
     d.    Template for Voicemail message:


"Hello [name of BP]. This is [name of SD tech] from the Global IT Service Desk. We would like to assist you with your concern about [main issue] with [ticket#]. Please reply to the email we will send you shortly. Thank you and have a good day".





     e.    Send an email to the business partner and use the:
Template for unsuccessful callback for email/self-service ticket that requires remote assistance:

Hi [name of business partner]


Thank you for contacting the Global IT Service Desk.

We received your concern about [insert issue here], and would like to assist you over the phone for troubleshooting. We were not able to reach you at [insert dialed phone# here].

For further assistance, please give us a call at [insert Regional SD phone# here] and quote your ticket number [insert ticket# here].


[name of SD analyst]
Global IT Service Desk
Servicedesk@help.wsp.com




D.  The WSP Service Desk 3-strike Rule:
     a.    The SD will follow a standard 3-strike rule for all active tickets with No Response Received from business partner.
     b.    The first communication sent to the business partner is considered the 1st strike.
     c.    The 2nd strike email will be sent by the ticket owner 24 hours after 1st strike email, if there has been no contact from the business partner.
     d.    The 3rd strike email will be sent 24 hours after the 2nd strike email, if there has been no contact from the business partner.
     e.    The ticket resolution notice will be sent 24 hours after the 3rd strike email and still no update from the business partner, and the ticket will be tagged as “Resolved” with “Closed – No Response” as Closure Reason.
     f.     No outbound calls are needed before sending emails from the 2nd strike to the ticket resolution notice.
     g.    If the business partner replies to the email, the 3-strike rule is reset.
     h.    The 3-strike rule applies only during local business hours (see WSP Global IT SD Guide file for list).
     i.     Follow templates for the 3-Strike rule emails:

Template for 2nd strike email:

Hi [name of business partner]


Good day!

We have not received a call from you about your concern with [insert issue here].

We would like to verify if your concern has been resolved. For further assistance, please give us a call at [insert Regional SD phone# here], and quote your ticket number [insert ticket# here].


[name of SD analyst]
Global IT Service Desk
Servicedesk@help.wsp.com




Template for 3rd strike email:

Hi [name of business partner]


Good day!

We would like to assist you with your issue about [insert issue here], but has not received any reply from you.

Please let us know if you still need help. For further assistance, please give us a call at [insert Regional SD phone# here], and quote your ticket number [insert ticket# here].


[name of SD analyst]
Global IT Service Desk
Servicedesk@help.wsp.com




Template for ticket resolution notice:

Hi [name of business partner]


Good day!

We regret that we have not received further contact from you regarding your concern with [insert issue here].

Your Incident Ticket [insert ticket# here] has now been set to “resolved” status. If you still need help, please get in touch with us, using your preferred contact method, or for immediate assistance, please give us a call at [insert Regional SD phone# here] and we will be happy to assist you promptly.


[name of SD analyst]
Global IT Service Desk
Servicedesk@help.wsp.com






[IMPORTANT UPDATE] Handling interactions for existing tickets in WSP ServiceNow

To facilitate a more efficient way of handling follow-up for existing tickets, RITMS’s, or Tasks in WSP ServiceNow, we will follow the steps below:

•    Ticket numbers without the zero’s after the INC, are WSP SNOW tickets
•    Search for the RITM or Task in Atos SNOW, to verify that it is not opened in our system.
•    We will not check the status of the WSP tickets with the Canada SME’s but instead ask the user as much information as we can, as tactfully as we can.
•    We will inform the business partner that we no longer have access to the old ticket system, but what we will do is open one from our end, and escalate it to the dedicated team that handles existing tickets in the WSP SNOW, so that the ticket can be resolved or updated.
•    Inform the business partner that an update will be provided to them as soon as possible.
•    Log the ticket and route it to ZZ.ServiceDesk.SwivelSeat.WSP, using GENERIC_ITEM, as “Affected CI”.
•    The Swivel Team will check the status of the WSP SNOW ticket, append the notes from it to the ATOS SNOW ticket and determine if the issue can be resolved by: ?L1 – assign the ticket back to the L1 who created the ticket.
       •    L2 – assign the ticket to the L2 queue
       •    Onsite – assign the ticket to the US.OSS.NEW.ALLIANCE, using Alliance_Generic_CI, as “Affected CI”.
       •    Other support group – assign the WSP Ticket to the WSP Support Group, if not escalated yet.
•    L1/L2 will take ownership of the tickets assigned back to them from the Swivel Team, and endorse to Queue Manager if unable to follow up with the business partner.

Request a Call” Handling Process – WSP Global IT Service Desk

I.  Objective
     To setup a standard process for handling “Request a Call” from business partners using OneContact.

II.  Scopes and Limitations:
     a.    Service Desk L1 analysts will receive the scheduled “Request a Call” from OneContact on Genesys.
     b.    L1 agent will receive a pop-up notification on Genesys, and needs to accept a scheduled “Request a Call”.
     c.    Genesys will automatically dial the business partner’s preferred phone number, and the L1 will automatically be on “Outbound” status.
     d.    L1 will follow the “Outbound Call Flow” in handling “Request a Call” interactions.
     e.    L1 will log the “Request a Call” as a “Phone” Contact Type on the Incident Ticket.
     f.     L1 will follow the Incident Ticket Management Process, on a successful ”Request a Call” interaction.
     g.    L1 will have one call back attempt to the business partner when the first call out was unsuccessful.
     h.    L1 will leave a voicemail message (when VM is available) and send an email to the business partner, when the second dial out was unsuccessful.
     i.     L1 will document the unsuccessful “Request a Call”, tag it as “Resolved, with “Closed – No Response” as the Closure Reason.
     j.     L1 will follow the “Disconnected Call/Chat SOP” on the Incident Ticket Follow up Process, for disconnected outbound call, during troubleshooting.

III.  Supporting Documents:

     a.    Voicemail Template:


"Hello [name of business partner]. This is [name of SD tech] from the Global IT Service Desk. We regret that you were not able to take the requested call back. Please schedule another call request or call us back at [give Regional SD phone #]. Thank you and have a good day".





     b.    Email Template:

Template for unsuccessful “Request a Call” callback

Hi [name of business partner]


Good day!

We were not able to reach your phone number [insert dialed phone #’s], on the time slot you chose for the call back request from OneContact.

If you still need help, please schedule another “Request a Call”, or you can reach us using chat or email.

For further assistance, please give us a call at [insert Regional SD phone# here], and we will be happy to assist you.


[name of SD analyst]
Global IT Service Desk
Servicedesk@help.wsp.com

Self-Service Ticket Handling Process – WSP Global IT Service Desk

I.  Objective:
     To setup a standard process for handling Self-Service Tickets submitted by WSP Global employees.

II.  Scopes and Limitations:
     a.    Self-service tickets will be extracted from ServiceNow on a regular interval (at least every 15 minutes, depending on volume) by the Queue Manager.
     b.    The Queue Manager will assign the Self-Service Tickets to the available L1 agents on the shift.
     c.    L1 on shift should monitor his assigned tickets, regularly, during the shift to make sure that he is able to address Self-service tickets promptly.
     d.    L1 will make a call back on issues that require troubleshooting over the phone or remote session.
     e.    L1 will utilize the “Additional comments (Customer visible)” field on ServiceNow to communicate with business partners, to follow-up on Self-Service tickets that do not require troubleshooting or remote session.
     f.     L1 will use the standard email templates applicable to the ticket/issue.
     g.    L1 will log the email sent to the business partner via the “Additional comments (Customer visible)” on the “Work Notes” field on the Incident Ticket.
     h.    L1 will leave a voicemail message (when VM is available) and send an email via the “Additional comments (Customer visible)” to the end business partner, after an unsuccessful call back attempt.


"Hello [name of BP]. This is [name of SD tech] from the Global IT Service Desk. We would like to assist you with your concern about [main issue] with [ticket#. Please reply to the email we will send you shortly. Thank you and have a good day".

     i.    When the business partner replies to the follow-up email that they got through the “Additional comments (Customer visible)”, and it goes to the Genesys queue, then the succeeding outbound emails can be sent from Genesys by utilizing the “reply” option.
     j.    L1 will follow the 3-strike rule for all active self-service tickets when there is no further interaction from business partner.

III.  Standard Email templates for Self-Service Tickets:

Template for unsuccessful callback for email/self-service ticket that requires remote assistance :

Hi [name of business partner]


Thank you for contacting the Global IT Service Desk.

We received your concern about [insert issue here], and would like to assist you over the phone for troubleshooting. We were not able to reach you at [insert dialed phone# here].

For further assistance, please give us a call at [insert Regional SD phone# here] and quote your ticket number [insert ticket# here].


[name of SD analyst]
Global IT Service Desk
Servicedesk@help.wsp.com




Template for advising that the ticket will be escalated to other Support Group :

Hi [name of business partner]


Thank you for contacting the Global IT Service Desk.

We received your issue about [insert issue here], with Incident Ticket [insert ticket# here]. We verified that this issue should be addressed by the [insert general name of Support Group here] Team.

[Provide brief explanation why the ticket is going to be escalated to another group]


[name of SD analyst]
Global IT Service Desk
Servicedesk@help.wsp.com
